1. Introduction to Version Control
Before diving into Git, it's essential to understand Version Control Systems (VCS) and why they are useful.
What is Version Control?
Version Control is a system that records changes to a file or set of files over time. It helps in:
 ‚úÖ Keeping track of changes made to the code.
 ‚úÖ Allowing multiple developers to work on the same project without conflicts.
 ‚úÖ Restoring previous versions of files if needed.
 ‚úÖ Collaborating efficiently in software development.
Types of Version Control Systems
Local Version Control ‚Äì All changes are stored on your computer (e.g., saving multiple copies of files manually).
Centralized Version Control (CVCS) ‚Äì A single server stores all versions of a project (e.g., SVN, Perforce).
Distributed Version Control (DVCS) ‚Äì Each user has a full copy of the repository (e.g., Git, Mercurial).
üí° Git is a Distributed Version Control System (DVCS), meaning every developer has a full history of the project.

2. Installing Git
Before using Git, you need to install it on your system.
Windows
Download Git from Git for Windows.
Run the installer and select the default settings.
Verify the installation by running:
