13. Git Best Practices, Performance Optimization, and CI/CD Integration
Now that you understand Git troubleshooting, recovery, and advanced collaboration techniques, let‚Äôs dive into best practices, optimizing Git performance, and integrating Git with Continuous Integration/Continuous Deployment (CI/CD).

13.1 Git Best Practices
Following best practices in Git ensures clean, maintainable, and efficient version control.
üîπ 1. Follow a Consistent Branching Strategy
Using a branching model makes it easier to collaborate and manage code. Some popular branching strategies:
‚úÖ Git Flow (Ideal for Large Teams)
main ‚Üí Stable, production-ready code
develop ‚Üí Ongoing development
feature/* ‚Üí Each new feature has its own branch
hotfix/* ‚Üí Quick fixes to production issues
‚úÖ GitHub Flow (Ideal for Small Teams & CI/CD)
main ‚Üí Always deployable
feature-branch ‚Üí Short-lived branch for new features
pull request ‚Üí Merged when feature is complete
‚úÖ Trunk-Based Development (For Fast Deployment)
main ‚Üí Frequent merges with feature flags

üîπ 2. Write Meaningful Commit Messages
Follow the "Imperative Mood" style for commit messages:
 ‚úÖ Good:
feat: Add authentication to user login
fix: Resolve memory leak in checkout process
chore: Update dependencies in package.json

‚ùå Bad:
Fixed bug
Updated code
Changed something

‚úÖ Follow Conventional Commit Format
<type>(<scope>): <description>

feat: New feature
fix: Bug fix
chore: Maintenance
docs: Documentation updates
test: Adding tests
style: Code formatting
refactor: Code restructuring

üîπ 3. Use .gitignore to Avoid Unwanted Files
Before committing, ensure unnecessary files (logs, compiled files, dependencies, etc.) are ignored.
